## 1. SERP Intent Analysis

### 1a. Dominant Content Format

The top SERP result is a Wikipedia definition/reference article. The People Also Ask questions split between definitional queries ("What do they mean by studio apartment?"), financial comparison queries ("Is it cheaper to live in a studio or one-bedroom?"), and high-volume transactional/local queries (studio apartments in Chicago under $1,000, Los Angeles under $1,500, etc.).

The Claude AI response in Data Source 3 produced a hybrid format: structured comparison guide with decision framework, rent tables, and platform breakdown. This is a **hybrid reference + decision guide** format.

**Recommended format:** A utility-first decision guide that opens with a clear definition, moves quickly into practical comparison content (subtypes, rent ranges, decision framework), and closes with FAQs. This matches both the informational anchor of the SERP (Wikipedia-style definition coverage) and the commercial decision intent visible in the PAA and local queries.

Do NOT brief a listicle. Do NOT brief a pure definition article. The format is: **definition anchor + decision guide with comparison tables + FAQ tail.**

