**H2: Is a Studio Apartment Right for You?**
*[CONTENT GAP: No competitor in Data Source 1 provides a structured decision framework. This is the highest-value section for differentiating from Wikipedia and capturing commercial-intent searchers.]*

*Writing instruction: Present two clearly labeled lists (works well / creates friction) as a practical decision tool. Be honest about the tradeoffs. Include remote work specifically as a friction point, since this is the most common regret reason based on post-pandemic renter behavior. Do not frame this as promotional. The goal is to give the reader the honest answer, even if it means they conclude a studio is not right for them.*

**Studio works well when:**
- You are a solo renter with minimal possessions
- You treat your home primarily as a base for sleeping and morning routines
- The rent savings allow you to afford a significantly better neighborhood than a one-bedroom would
- You can create a dedicated work zone (alcove, converted closet desk, or room divider setup)

**Studio creates friction when:**
- You work from home full-time without a defined, separate desk area
- You have frequent overnight guests or a regular partner situation
- You own significant gear, instruments, hobby equipment, or furniture
- You have a pet over 30 lbs (spatial friction, and many buildings have size restrictions)

